name: Trumansburg, 1964
description: Robert Moog received a grant of $16,000 from the New York State Small Business Association and began work in Trumansburg, New York, not far from the Cornell campus.

name: New York City, 1968
description: In 1968, Wendy Carlos released Switched-On Bach, an album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer. It won three Grammy Awards and was the first classical album certified platinum. She would go on to produce music for the soundtrack of "A Clockwork Orange."

name: ABC Studios, 1969
description: Dick Hyman releases "Moog: The Electric Eclectics Of Dick Hyman" in 1969, which would become his biggest hit album.

name: California, 1970s
description: In the 1970s, at the height of the Moog's popularity, it became ubiquitous as part of progressive rock bands such as Yes, Tangerine Dream, and Emerson, Lake & Palmer. It was also adopted by jazz musicians including Herbie Hancock, Jan Hammer and Sun Ra.
